During my undergraduate coursework at Harvard, I have taken coursework on data visualization in R. As a brief illustration of my skills, here are three examples which are all maps. The first visualization is the New York City Map split by counties that shows data from 2009 by the department of health of diabetes rates across each county. This is an interactive graph, therefore, when clicked on each county, the rate is displayed. The second visualization is also a map but this time of the United States that shows the median income by veterans across the country and it is also an interactive graph. The third visualization is a simple but interesting one that also displays the nyc map by neighborhoods and the rates at which pit-bull dogs are owned and licensed across the city.

Diabetes Rates Across NYC Counties in 2010

This map of New York City showing each individual county is mapped to diabetes rates across the city. This data was derived from the Community Health Survey conducted in 2010 that asks adults across the city if they have been diagnosed by a doctor with diabetes. This graph is specifically interesting because oftentimes health and income are associated with one another. In this case, areas of the city that are relatively higher in income such as the Upper East side are relatively low in terms of diabetes rates as compared to Brownsville or Brooklyn for example that have much higher rates of diabetes.

 

Veterans’ Income Across the United States by Counties (2023)

Being able to depict a variable across a map can tell you more than just the variable itself. For example in this visualization, it depicts veterans’ income across U.S. counties as of 2023. This data was derived from the United States Department of Agriculture. Asides from the fact that you can click on each county and it tells you the median income of veterans in that area, the map also serves as a way of highlighting the areas where veterans tend to reside the most. For example, we can see that Utah and Alaska as compared to the northeastern states. Additionally, Veterans’ income is relatively higher in these areas. As you click through each county, you can see how income varies.

Number of Pit Bulls Owned Across New York City

This visualization portrays the rates of owned pit-bulls across New York City neighborhoods that are licensed. I was interested in looking at Pit Bulls specifically because they are a heavily stereotyped dog seen as “intimidating”. What was surprising to find out is that most of the licensed dogs that are pit-bulls in NYC are concentrated in areas that are more disadvantaged like in Harlem, Brownsville, and East Flatbush. In contrast, not many pit bulls are licensed in the wealthier areas of NYC such as the Upper East Side or the West Village. Visualizing data that oftentimes can seen minuscule and unimportant, can often tell us more about the makeup of an area than we think.
